title: Cheap and simple X/Y axis center calibration

description.text:
Simple to use, cheap to print, calibrate you X/Y center and horizontal shrinkage in under 15 minutes

*****STEP 1
Open your slicer of choice and place the tool dead center on the build plate, slice at around 0.25mm and print

*****STEP 2
once print is finished and cooled, do not remove tool from build plate, simply measure from the edge of the build plate to the point of the tool and calculate the difference on each axis
for example....

X axis
left side build plate to tool 90mm
right side build plate to tool 70mm

the difference being 20mm

repeat for Y axis going from top and bottom of build plate to point of tool

*****STEP 3

now divide your answers by 2 which will give you the correct amount of adjustment you need to centralise your prints, now just add your new values into your firmware

for those who don't have access to the firmware can use the following start Gcode in your machine settings:

G21
G90
G28 X0 Y0
G28 Z0
G1 Z5.0 F3000
G92 X??? Y??? Z15 ; Sets position as the new X/Y position
G92 E0
G1 F200 E4
G92 E0

This Gcode works for me on my Anet A8, you may have your own start setup so the main bit you could probably add to yours is the G92 code with your values added (not the extruder just the main G92)

*****STEP 4

Now remove the tool and measure it, it should come out exactly 60mm from point to point across each axis with a 10 mm hole in center, if not then make adjustments to your Horizontal Expansion in your slicer

*****STEP 5

run print cool and measure again but with all the new values, it should now print centralised and shrink to the correct values

The frame

I also add a small cube minus a cylinder to make a loop so it can be easily attached.

The main part of the snowflake

I use the same method to make the central hexagon of this part.
I add a long cube to make 2 of the main branches then I make the other 4 by rotating this cube using a loop.
Each main branch is holding 6 small branches made using 6 cubes. I make one then I make the other 5 using a loop again.
Finally, I make a hole for the axis of the central part using a cylinder.

I use the same method again to make an hexagon.
I just add an axis using a cylinder so it can spin.

description.text:
This is the battery holder/tray/box (whatever it's called) for the Nerf Phoenix LTX tagger. It is a two part print. Before you print it, make sure each box lays down flat on its back to avoid having to clean up all the support structures. The "front" may require a small support structure in order to hold up the little tab that keeps the battery cover from fitting on backward. I printed them with the adhesion plate to help keep them from prematurely breaking loose from the print bed. Once the two halves are printed, they need to be glued back-to-back. The cut outs for the springs should be next to each other. and the small hole in the back of each one should line up. Super glue works real well on PLA and sets up in about 5 seconds. Get them lined up right or you'll be printing off a second set.

To complete this build, you'll also need 7 "AA Battery Positive Negative Conversion Spring Contact Plates". They are what hold the batteries in the holder; they are shown in a few of the pictures. A small amount of hot glue will help hold them in place. Only one battery polarity is marked on each piece. BE SURE YOU GET THE CONTACT PLATES AND BATTERIES INSTALLED CORRECTLY. Compare them carefully with the original. If you get them backward, you will most likely fry your tagger. Also, you can cut down one of the AA plates to make the piece to will come out the side of the front piece. This is where the tagger will pull 4.5v instead of the full 9v of the whole pack. I have successfully tested this and it does indeed work!

AA Battery Plates from Amazon: http://amzn.to/2Cd09ZC

If you find this useful, consider sending me a dollar or two. I'd sure appreciate it.

The walls are pretty thin but have to be so that it will fit into the tagger. It should hold the batteries just fine since there shouldn't be any stress on it once it is inside the tagger.

After it is printed, the 2 pieces need to be glued together. After the glue dries, make sure the box can physically fit into the tagger. If not, the edges can be shaved down slightly to help make it fit.

description.text:
The Dolphin was printed using Colorfabb Bronzefill. The model needs supports. To avoid a lot of sanding I actually printed the model in two halves and glued it back together. In this way no supports are needed. To create the two halves I loaded to model in Cura, lowered it beneath the build plate by approx half, duplicated the model and rotated it 180 degrees. After printing and glueing, a lot of sanding is needed to bring out the bronze (120, 240, 400 and 600 pt, and then polish).

The base was printed using Colorfabb NGEN clear for the outer walls, and Colorfabb PLA Ultra Marine Blue for the infill. This can be done in Cura by using the infill override setting to the second extruder (i.e. you need a dual extruder setup). I increased the outer wall thickness to 1.8 mm and left the top/bottom to 0.8 mm.
The result is a blueish sea with white foam on top.

Plate temp: 60 dC
Print speed: 60 mm/s
Nozzle temp: 200 for Bronzefill & PLA, 220 for NGEN clear.
The Dolphin and base have been designed using Blender. I'm aware the models still have some minor artefacts. Cura did not have any problems slicing the input though.

title: BL Touch i3 V2.1 front mount

description.text:
Like cooler ducts, there are many probe mounts available for the i3. I didn't like any of them - or the ones I did like wouldn't work with my machine. I've a rear-mounted T-Rex cooler (excellent btw - search Thing for it) so my options were limited to a front-mounted thing.

I wanted to get as close as possible to the probe, securely mounted, without obstructing the front view. My Marlin offsets are as follows:

X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 9
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -38
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -1.0

As ever with probes and mounts, BE CAREFUL when you're dialling this in. The probe, when raised, is only about 2-3mm higher than the nozzle. Start high and work lower till you get your own settings right!

Note: this is for the BL Touch Smart. I've been told it doesn't quite fit the Classic (pin too low when retracted) - happy to redesign if anyone is able to work with me to test it.

description.text:
Description of the 3D model

This model is the evolution of low poly crocodile posted previously.
It presents 3 (see 4) kinds of solutions for the rotation and the movement of the parts of the model.
So he became a "Croco Action".

The impression:

the files are printable at scale or at 125%. Below 100% some parts are too small. The file (PieceJoint) must be printed at 100% filling and with support on the pieces (not only on the board). For the other file (body) I recommend a light support (angle to 70%), even if their absence is not problematic. For the thickness of the outline (of the wall or the shell ....) I recommend 2mm.

Mounting

So there are 2 STL files: -> [crocoCorps] gathers the different members of the model (the torso, the arms, etc) (cf photo membres.jpg) -> [crocoPieceJoint] is made up of the elements which allow the rotation and the assembly of members (see photo pieceJoint.jpg)

-The arms and legs are assembled to the body by the small hinge model (see photo charn_Petite.jpg). In addition these members are held in place by a small piece that is placed (with a clamp) at the beveled end of the hinge. This end goes into the torso, the other end goes into the arms and legs.

-> How to:

-Assemble the jaw with the head (see photo tete.jpg). It is useless to push the axle too far into the holes. We cut the part of the axis that exceeds.
-Assemble the hand and arms (see photo Bras.jpg). We cut the part of the axis that exceeds.
-Assemble the big hinges and the small ones (the cylinders serve as axis), then introduce them in the arms and the legs, then place the legs and the arms in the torso and finally one places the small parts to hold these members (this operation is delicate because it is necessary to clean beforehand the parts of the residues of the printing).
-finally we introduce the big hinges in the head and in the tail, then in the torso (see photo Char-tete.jpg).

Voilà Have Fun.

Note: when the parts becomming loose just put on and let glue dry on the hinges.

description.text:
Abacus: Seven Digits, Two Versions, 90mm x 140mm, Chinese or Japanese, designed for easy assembly.

The abacus is an ancient calculator that comes in various styles, still used widely in Asian cultures as a way to help children build number sense or as a toy. It makes a nice-looking multi-wheeled toy car or a sound shaker like maracas!

The Chinese abacus has seven beads on a vertical bar, while the Japanese version has five beads on a vertical bar. As a general rule, each bead in the lower deck represents one when moved toward to center beam. Each bead in the upper deck represents five when moved to the center beam. On the Japanese abacus, each bar could represent zero to nine units. By contrast, the Chinese abacus allows the representation of zero through 15 units on each bar, thus supporting calculation using the base-16 system. For the base-10 system, the two beads at the very top and bottom are not used. About the decimal point, users could, in fact, choose their own place, depending on their specific needs. So as you can see, the abacus is a blend of concrete and abstract representations.

As always, small parts can be dangerous for small children; please educate young children not to put little parts in their mouth and follow all safety procedures when working with young children. Have fun making and playing on your abacus!

If you like Android apps, my Android app is at https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=appinventor.ai_moodle_bu.TouchAbacusforKids

title: Home Mini Outlet Cover Wall Mount

description.text:
This is a wall mount for a Google Home Mini designed to install in place of the outlet cover of a standard GFI outlet (as frequently found in bathrooms). It should require only a few tools and no additional hardware to install.

The mount includes a short stand-off to allow you to wrap the Mini's USB cord around the mount for a cleaner look. The Mini sits in the bracket held in place by two tabs. The slide switch is accessible while the Mini is in the mount, and the Mini can also be easily removed to access to reset switch.

If you would like to remix this model, for example to make it work with different outlet designs, you can find the Fusion 360 model to copy and modify at Google Home Mini Outlet Cover Wall Mount.

Notes:

The bracket and the plate should be simple prints on most 3D printers. I printed mine using PolyMaker PC-Max filament for extra strength, but PLA works fine as well. The plate can be printed without supports. The bracket needs supports underneath the outlet cover. I just used the supports automatically generated by my slicer, Cura.

Support Cleanup and Installation



Cleanup:

  • Most of the support structure holds up a large flat surface, which made removal surprisingly easy; I was able to lever out the support structure in large pieces with a flat head screwdriver
  • Remember to remove the small support structures in the notches that the mounting plate slides into; it's a lot easier to do before you mount the bracket to the wall (lesson learned!)
  • None of the surfaces that have supports attached will be visible after the bracket is installed, so no additional cleanup is needed
  • The small mounting holes in the plate are 2mm in diameter, small in size compared to most printer nozzles, so may not print cleanly or at that exact size; they can easily be cleaned up using a 2mm or 5/64 in drill bit

Installation:

  • The plate attaches to the back of the Google Home Mini using the four T6 Torx screws that hold the back of the case in place
  • You need to remove the rubber disk glued to the base of the Mini
  • I was able to remove the rubber disk by gently prying an edge up with a knife and very slowly peeling it away; it is attached with strong double-sided tape
  • For more in-depth instructions, including tips on using heat to make the rubber disk easier to remove, see Justin Alvey's excellent Google Home Mini teardown
  • The four Torx screws that hold the Mini's case back on should work fine to attach the plate through the case back, but you can also get slightly longer Torx screws if you are worried about using the ones that come with the Mini
  • The bracket installs in place of the stock GFI outlet cover plate using the same screws that hold on the outlet cover plate

See attached photos for details on support removal, mounting holes, and how the whole thing goes together.

description.text:
So you've got a CNC Router, and a 3D printer, and a small lathe - the world's your oyster! why are you paying a couple of hundred £ for a dust shoe....?

Well, maybe you don't have much spare time, or you're filthy rich. But assuming you're not...

I made a Sphinx by Kyo, and got bored with sitting there with a hoover trying to catch all the dust that was being generated. I've also recently taught myself how to use Fusion 360 and wanted a more interesting project to try.

The good news - is it works exceptionally well! I couldn't detect any dust at all escaping while cutting. It's cheap (cost me around £30), it's lightweight and looks the part too.

The bad news, it's a bit involved and needs a bit of skill to make and put together.

This design is dependent on you having the mount from Chris Laidlaw. If you've made a Sphinx, and bought his plates, you've probably seen the flyer for the mount. http://chrisclub.wixsite.com/prototype-machining. Chris also does his own dust shoe design too.

I can thoroughly reccomend this router mount if you haven't yet bought one. Save the money on the Openbuilds mount and any store bought dust shoe, and you could buy one of these mounts instead and make your own shoe.

The design allows enough clearance to miss all parts of the machine structure, isn't overly heavy and you can wind it all the way up for access to the cutter and spindle locking button on the router.

You can get some 2" brush strip cheaply from Amazon: https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B016IXK42Q/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

This works really well, and you get 2 strips so you can replace the brushes when necessary. The only downside is you need to bend it carefully by hand. Which can be a bit time consuming and frustrating. Just take your time, and if you have them, some small clamps really help to form it around the acrylic base plate.

I actually cut the strip a bit too short accidentally, which leaves a small gap. In testing, it looks like this could actually help direct and control the airflow.

Hoover hose is cheap enough: https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B000W5HQGY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

You'll have to cut one end off, and glue on a new end ring. I've included an STL file so you can print one. Glue it with Loctite 60 seconds all purpose superglue. Works really well on PETG and PLA. Don't forget the clip ring first before you glue the new end on :-)

The Henry hoover is cheap and supplies plenty of suction. It's also small enough to sit neatly under a bench.

You can get a bit of 10mm Acrylic sheet for £2.54 (plus shipping) from here: https://www.materials4me.co.uk/Plastics/Extruded-Acrylic/Sheet/p/261800

That's big enough to give you 2 goes at it. I ran a second one as the rebate for the brush needed to be a bit bigger for it to sit right.

The support pillar is made from a piece of 19mm ali bar stock. A single 10" length is enough, but at £1.56, it's worth getting a couple just in case:
https://www.materials4me.co.uk/Metal/Aluminium/Round-Bar/p/289

The 2 retaining rings are made from 40mm bar stock, you only need about 4":
https://www.materials4me.co.uk/Metal/Aluminium/Round-Bar/p/256971

Note - the photo i've supplied of the turned parts shows the support pillar before I turned down the thicker bottom section to allow it to be raised higher.

I'm using M3x20mm machine screws, each with a washer either side of the plastic components, and a nylok nut. You'll need 7 sets of that in total.

There's a single M5 x 25mm machine screw holding the support pillar components and the acrylic plate together.

The public link to the design on Fusion 360 is here so you can generate your tool paths:
http://a360.co/2l884zZ

Hopefully that should all work ok. Leave some comments or shoot me a private message if you're having trouble.

Have fun!

description.text:
-Got a PS4 Pro recently and wanted an under desk mount because I don't have enough table space. Saw several other mounts out there, but decided to make my own.
-I left a small gap above the mount to allow for a bit of an airspace.
-Mounts are about 4.5 inches long which is pretty much the max for my Monoprice Select mini.
-Printed at a fat layer height because I didn't care about resolution. Still took most of my life to print two of them in one go.
-Printed vertically so that I wouldn't end up with the weight of unit pulling against laminated layers.
-Printed with 100% infill so it would be as strong as possible.
-Left a bit of play between the tangs which engage the PS4 Pro and the arms which slide beneath the unit so that it wouldn't be too tight a fit.
-I was concerned about overall strength, that's why I made the mounts with a .187 wall thickness along with some buttressing at the top to resist flex.. I'm thinking you'd have to have about a dozen PS4 pro's stacked up to break these.
-Screw holes are .180 in diameter with a clearance hole of .400 diameter for the head.
-Sorry for the crappy cell phone photo of the mounted unit. I'm quite ashamed of its terrible quality but I'm too tired to do any better today.

title: Anycubic I3 Mega Spool Holder Remix with filament guide

description.text:
This is a remix of "Spool holder for Anycubic I3 Mega" by kurioso.
I really like the original, but the parts were a little loose and I had problems with the spool not staying on and filament getting tangled.

I've made the following changes to the arm

  • moved the spool closer to the Z-axis mount
  • tightened the z-axis post clip so there is less play
  • thickened the spool holder arm slightly so the cylinder fits tighter
  • modified the brace to be at w 45 degree angle rather than horizontal at the top so it prints without supports and still provides strength near the top of the arm where the twisting will happen.
  • and maybe the most important change, I've added a filament guide.

The original cylinder fits this arm so I did not include the cylinder model.
The arm from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2681737 also works well. I have one of each.

Since I had issues with the arm twisting and spools coming off of the original model, I wanted a bigger lip on the spool cylinder. I didn't want to print another cylinder so I modeled a small lip piece to glue on the original. I've included this part as well.

I noticed someone asked for kurioso's fusion 360 model. Since I converted the original arm to a solid to make my changes, I've included the 123d design files as well.

title: Mold For Rubber Dampener For Copter Skids

description.text:
On the skids of my used copter that I bounght was such a rubber thingi missing.

I made this mold and used usual silicon to make new ones.

Use a bit of soapwater for the mold, so the silicom will get off easier. Use clamps to fix the mold and inject the silicone. Leave it at least a night, better 24 hours, closed.
They are a bit softer and not that beautiful but they to the job. I use two white on the front and the original black ones on the rear.
They fit onto a 12 mm tube.

Print with 0.1 mm for a nicer surface.

UPDATE: Since the silicon is quite soft, I made a V2 where the thinner wall are thicker ;)

I added the freecad-files and the positive form as well for thoose, who want to print it directly with flexible filament.
